niversite yÄ±llarÄ±nda bunun yerine \"usb tak-&ccedil;alÄ±ÅtÄ±r &ccedil;Ä±kar evde bir daha tak &ccedil;alÄ±ÅtÄ±r\" metodunu kullanmak zorunda kalÄ±yorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>&Uuml;niversitelere y&uuml;zlerce olanak saÄlanÄ±rken y&ouml;netenlerin bunu takip etmemesinden dolayÄ± sizinde mahrum kalmanÄ±za neden olunuyorsa</li>\n<li>Kendi verdiÄi stajÄ± zorunlu staj yerine saymayan bir yerlerdeyseniz</li>\n<li>\"Bizim mezunlarÄ±mÄ±z &ccedil;ok talep g&ouml;r&uuml;yor\" diyip 3\'den fazla firma ismi sayÄ±lamÄ±yorsa</li>\n<li>E buna baÄlÄ± olarak tabi ki yurt dÄ±ÅÄ±na &ccedil;Ä±ktÄ±ÄÄ±nÄ±zda okulunuzun isminden esame okunmuyorsa</li>\n<li>GiriÅimciliÄin veya startup k&uuml;lt&uuml;r&uuml;n&uuml;n kÄ±rÄ±ntÄ±larÄ± yoksa ya da elle tutulut &ouml;rneÄi yoksa</li>\n<li>B&ouml;yle bir k&uuml;lt&uuml;re sahipseniz ve kendinizi garip ve herkes size bakÄ±yormuÅ gibi hissediyorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>Proje ve &ouml;devleriniz yaratÄ±cÄ±lÄ±ktan i&ccedil;ermekten yoksun ameleliklerle doluysa</li>\n<li>Database management dersini alabilmeden mezun olabilemenizi saÄlayan a&ccedil;Ä±klar varsa</li>\n<li>4 sene boyunca functional programalama kullanarak object oriented dilleri bile dize getirenler varsa</li>\n<li>Kendi lab\'Ä±nÄ±za isminiz orada g&uuml;venliÄe bildirilmemiÅse giremiyorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>E tabi yine buna baÄlÄ± olarak bir araya gelip proje yapma oranÄ±nÄ±n yapmama oranÄ±nÄ±n yanÄ±nda solda sÄ±fÄ±r kaldÄ±ÄÄ± durumlarda</li>\n<li>VoltranÄ±n par&ccedil;alarÄ±nÄ± toplar gibi sÄ±rf ortalamasÄ± tuttuÄu i&ccedil;in yandal,&ccedil;iftanadal yaparak par&ccedil;alar birleÅince fezaya u&ccedil;acaÄÄ±nÄ± sananlar baya &ccedil;oÄunluktaysa</li>\n<li>Bir onu &ouml;Ärenmeye &ccedil;alÄ±ÅÄ±p birde buna bakÄ±yÄ±m diyip sÄ±rf herkes &ouml;Äreniyo diye bir bok &ouml;Ärenemeden sona gelen adamlarÄ±n sayÄ±sÄ± &ccedil;oksa (bende b&ouml;yleydim bir aralar)</li>\n<li>K&uuml;t&uuml;phaneniz gece 12 gibi abs&uuml;rd bir saatte kapanÄ±yorsa ( &uuml;niversitedeydik deÄil mi yanlÄ±Å hatÄ±rlamÄ±yorum ? )</li>\n<li>Okumaya niyeti olmayan adamlarÄ±n okulun burs imkanlarÄ±ndan okumaya niyeti olanlardan daha fazla yararlanÄ±yorsa ve sizde buna anlam veremiyorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>2. sÄ±nÄ±f sonuna geldiÄinizde artÄ±k okulun size birÅey katamayacaÄÄ±nÄ± d&uuml;Å&uuml;n&uuml;yorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>Bu y&uuml;zden okuldan uzaklaÅÄ±p iÅ hayatÄ±na atÄ±lÄ±yorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>Buna baÄlÄ± olarak ortalamanÄ±zÄ± d&uuml;Å&uuml;r&uuml;yorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>Genel m&uuml;hendislik derslerinin egoist hocalarÄ±yla uÄraÅmak zorunda kalÄ±yorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>Dersleri ingilizce\'nin Ä°\'sini hazÄ±rlÄ±kta &ouml;Ärenmeden ge&ccedil;en adamlarla okuyorsanÄ±z</li>\n<li>Ve bu adamlarÄ±n nedense GPA\'si sizden y&uuml;kseklerdeyse</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2011-10-07 11:12:13','2011-10-07 11:12:13'),(19,1,'not-dead-yet','Not Dead, Yet','<p><img src=\"/static/images/uploads/notdeadyet.jpg\" align=\"left\"/>I was busy for a while that I couldnt find a time or excitement to write a blog post on whats going on or at least what I am doing for a while actually I am using <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/burakdede\">twitter</a> more than enough for that purpose. Lets cut to the chase, I was busy with my summer school taking courses (Signal&amp;Systems, Engineering Management etc) and rest of the time I try to hack new things mostly. For about almost 2-3 weeks I try to implement my own project that I developed for android that had some unfinished business. Than I got request from one of gsm companies to implement application for their brand. I almost finished developing application that I can say my progress about %90 right now. I got some design and code review things to do with project other than that I am done with it for a while.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I try to grasp deep knowladge about python world cause I have both stand alone and web projects that waiting to be implemented with python. I started for a while with <a href=\"http://zedshaw.com/\">Zed Shaw\'s </a><a href=\"http://learnpythonthehardway.org/\">Learn Python The Hard Way</a> book then move on to Mark Lutz <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Learning-Python-Powerful-Object-Oriented-Programming/dp/0596158068/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1312924935&amp;sr=1-1\">Learning Python</a>. I can recommend Zed\'s book for new starters its a good book mostly direct you to self learning and searching. Mark Lutz book is more elaborate and detailed&nbsp;on this topic providing really deep theoretical knowladge for about 200 pages, some people dont like this they want to directly jump into hello world =&gt; syntax =&gt; expressions =&gt; data structures and goes like that. I was reading the latest version of Mark\'s book which covers Python 3.0 not common use right now but will be in the future and you can learn whats new with that version. Because there are not so much projects using Python 3.0 in order to really understand changes with versions I am still reading Python 2.5 version of the book which you can find <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Learning-Python-3rd-Mark-Lutz/dp/0596513984/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1312924935&amp;sr=1-2\">here</a>. I forgot to mention but \"A byte of python\" is another great book that probably you can finish for about 1-2 hour its free also you can get it from <a href=\"http://www.swaroopch.com/notes/Python\">here</a>. And how about Python ? Well for short python is a language that designed for readability first in mind so code you have written looks very structured and thats one thing I wanna see in a language IMHO. Coming from Java background thats one thing I miss for a while (i think somebody said inner class, oh my). Other thing I like about Python that philosophy \"<em>Explicit is better than implicit</em>\". Yes you exactly see whats going on when you do things in Python I think this is one the things that differs Python from Ruby which allows you to do things \"magically\". You can get more of this from <a href=\"http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0020/\">Zen of Python</a>&nbsp;or by \"import this\". I will write more about Python and things interesting about design of it and comparison with languages I know. Thats it for a whille...</p>','<p><img src=\"/static/images/uploads/notdeadyet.jpg\" align=\"left\"/>I was busy for a while that I couldnt find a time or excitement to write a blog post on whats going on or at least what I am doing for a while actually I am using <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/burakdede\">twitter</a> more than enough for that purpose. Lets cut to the chase, I was busy with my summer school taking courses (Signal&amp;Systems, Engineering Management etc) and rest of the time I try to hack new things mostly. For about almost 2-3 weeks I try to implement my own project that I developed for android that had some unfinished business. Than I got request from one of gsm companies to implement application for their brand. I almost finished developing application that I can say my progress about %90 right now. I got some design and code review things to do with project other than that I am done with it for a while.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>I try to grasp deep knowladge about python world cause I have both stand alone and web projects that waiting to be implemented with python. I started for a while with <a href=\"http://zedshaw.com/\">Zed Shaw\'s </a><a href=\"http://learnpythonthehardway.org/\">Learn Python The Hard Way</a> book then move on to Mark Lutz <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Learning-Python-Powerful-Object-Oriented-Programming/dp/0596158068/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1312924935&amp;sr=1-1\">Learning Python</a>. I can recommend Zed\'s book for new starters its a good book mostly direct you to self learning and searching. Mark Lutz book is more elaborate and detailed&nbsp;on this topic providing really deep theoretical knowladge for about 200 pages, some people dont like this they want to directly jump into hello world =&gt; syntax =&gt; expressions =&gt; data structures and goes like that. I was reading the latest version of Mark\'s book which covers Python 3.0 not common use right now but will be in the future and you can learn whats new with that version. Because there are not so much projects using Python 3.0 in order to really understand changes with versions I am still reading Python 2.5 version of the book which you can find <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Learning-Python-3rd-Mark-Lutz/dp/0596513984/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1312924935&amp;sr=1-2\">here</a>. I forgot to mention but \"A byte of python\" is another great book that probably you can finish for about 1-2 hour its free also you can get it from <a href=\"http://www.swaroopch.com/notes/Python\">here</a>. And how about Python ? Well for short python is a language that designed for readability first in mind so code you have written looks very structured and thats one thing I wanna see in a language IMHO. Coming from Java background thats one thing I miss for a while (i think somebody said inner class, oh my). Other thing I like about Python that philosophy \"<em>Explicit is better than implicit</em>\". Yes you exactly see whats going on when you do things in Python I think this is one the things that differs Python from Ruby which allows you to do things \"magically\". You can get more of this from <a href=\"http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0020/\">Zen of Python</a>&nbsp;or by \"import this\". I will write more about Python and things interesting about design of it and comparison with languages I know. Thats it for a whille...</p>','2011-10-07 11:13:04','2011-10-07 11:24:21'),(20,1,'taskwhere-location-aware-task-management','TaskWhere : Location Aware Task Management','<p><img src=\"/static/images/uploads/task.jpg\" align=left alt=\"\"/>I have been implementing idea of mine for a while yes its a mobile app for Android, for now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>How did I come up with the idea ?</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>I was not happy with old traditional task management tools (or we can say todo list applications) like remember the milk, google tasks ( I am not saying these are not good products but they just dont fit to my style ). I keep looking at people who are using this kind of applications and they were like \"Ok I have this task no matter where I am I have to do this\" well short story I am not like that. Even if I am close to location where there is a task that I \"must\" do, sometimes I dont. (somebody should push me to do it :) ) Yes these task management tools have reminder but take this situation, think of that you have to get some kind of documents from student administration, you opened up your traditional task management tool, added it &amp; setted up reminder. Everything great up to here for me but if its a weekend and your application reminded you this task guess what you probably not even close to school and you probably just cancel the task and if remind you again you pissed of to application (even this is not application fault) and probably remove it. This is not seem as a effective way to get tasks done at least for me, you have to have some kind of location info attached to task and application must remind you not on time basis but on location. Yes this is my application idea in general.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>How did I developed this ?</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>I have been thinking about this for about a month, last week I can sit front of the computer and sketch some mock up (not professionally sketched ones just pen and paper) and when I looked at the general design it seems like application will be ready to use in one and half day when I looked at my abilities with location based apps. But guess what its not, absolutely not, cause appearantly my judge for project deadline is far from the real one. It took my 5 days actually finish application. By the way its open source you can check source code <a href=\"https://github.com/burakdd/TaskWhere\">@github</a>, add if you have ideas, create fork, I dont know do what ever you want. By the way application will be on <a href=\"https://market.android.com/\">Android market</a> very soon for free if you have time you can grab and install it. I will notify on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/burakdede\">twitter</a> when its on. Oh I forgot name of the application its <em><strong>TaskWhere.</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>How it works ?</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Basically you opened up application, create new task ( I specifically made it simple cause I have all these detailed todo list applications ) by providing location name, task and its location on the map. You can drag&amp;drop pin or search address on the map for task location. Oh wait I forgot something you can set proximity alert radius for that task. This can be default value but I am sure user will request to able to set it so I added it up. Now you have list of tasks with ability to do some quick actions like edit, mark as done, activate, deactivate just by clicking on item. Application also have service that runs on background even its interacting with user. When you enter the proximity area of the task TaskWhere will send notification and most importantly when you left the area, this is important cause you may discard first notification but I hope second one convince you to do it thats why I added.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>Is there any similar application ?</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Actually I dont know this cause I did not search in an extended way other than <a href=\"https://market.android.com/search?q=location+based+task&amp;so=1&amp;c=apps\">android market</a>, there is one but its working with private beta request. There are some iphone applications actually but they are not free well most of them.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>Future Ideas</strong></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Synchronization ( thinking of adding <a href=\"https://www.parse.com/\">Parse</a> support which makes server side deployment, maintanence easy for mobile applications it funded by YC go look at it its great you can read, insert your object key-value based storage, but you have to request invite first )</li>\r\n<li>GoogleTask Integration ( they have opened up <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/tasks/\">offical api</a> for this with Oauth integration etc. so it will be good to get this done )</li>\r\n<li>May be some ui changes cause design of application fully belongs to me, I have to confest this here I can say if two color fits each other estetically (meaning I can taste good design :) ) but I do not have much ability about turning some sketch into actual design.</li>\r\n</ul>','<p><img src=\"/static/images/uploads/task.jpg\" align=left alt=\"\"/>I have been implementing idea of mine for a while yes its a mobile app for Android, for now.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>How did I come up with the idea ?</strong></span></p>\n\n<p>I was not happy with old traditional task management tools (or we can say todo list applications) like remember the milk, google tasks ( I am not saying these are not good products but they just dont fit to my style ). I keep looking at people who are using this kind of applications and they were like \"Ok I have this task no matter where I am I have to do this\" well short story I am not like that. Even if I am close to location where there is a task that I \"must\" do, sometimes I dont. (somebody should push me to do it :) ) Yes these task management tools have reminder but take this situation, think of that you have to get some kind of documents from student administration, you opened up your traditional task management tool, added it &amp; setted up reminder. Everything great up to here for me but if its a weekend and your application reminded you this task guess what you probably not even close to school and you probably just cancel the task and if remind you again you pissed of to application (even this is not application fault) and probably remove it. This is not seem as a effective way to get tasks done at least for me, you have to have some kind of location info attached to task and application must remind you not on time basis but on location. Yes this is my application idea in general.</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>How did I developed this ?</strong></span></p>\n\n<p>I have been thinking about this for about a month, last week I can sit front of the computer and sketch some mock up (not professionally sketched ones just pen and paper) and when I looked at the general design it seems like application will be ready to use in one and half day when I looked at my abilities with location based apps. But guess what its not, absolutely not, cause appearantly my judge for project deadline is far from the real one. It took my 5 days actually finish application. By the way its open source you can check source code <a href=\"https://github.com/burakdd/TaskWhere\">@github</a>, add if you have ideas, create fork, I dont know do what ever you want. By the way application will be on <a href=\"https://market.android.com/\">Android market</a> very soon for free if you have time you can grab and install it. I will notify on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/burakdede\">twitter</a> when its on. Oh I forgot name of the application its <em><strong>TaskWhere.</strong></em></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>How it works ?</strong></span></p>\n\n<p>Basically you opened up application, create new task ( I specifically made it simple cause I have all these detailed todo list applications ) by providing location name, task and its location on the map. You can drag&amp;drop pin or search address on the map for task location. Oh wait I forgot something you can set proximity alert radius for that task. This can be default value but I am sure user will request to able to set it so I added it up. Now you have list of tasks with ability to do some quick actions like edit, mark as done, activate, deactivate just by clicking on item. Application also have service that runs on background even its interacting with user. When you enter the proximity area of the task TaskWhere will send notification and most importantly when you left the area, this is important cause you may discard first notification but I hope second one convince you to do it thats why I added.</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>Is there any similar application ?</strong></span></p>\n\n<p>Actually I dont know this cause I did not search in an extended way other than <a href=\"https://market.android.com/search?q=location+based+task&amp;so=1&amp;c=apps\">android market</a>, there is one but its working with private beta request. There are some iphone applications actually but they are not free well most of them.</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>Future Ideas</strong></span></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Synchronization ( thinking of adding <a href=\"https://www.parse.com/\">Parse</a> support which makes server side deployment, maintanence easy for mobile applications it funded by YC go look at it its great you can read, insert your object key-value based storage, but you have to request invite first )</li>\n<li>GoogleTask Integration ( they have opened up <a href=\"http://code.google.com/apis/tasks/\">offical api</a> for this with Oauth integration etc. so it will be good to get this done )</li>\n<li>May be some ui changes cause design of application fully belongs to me, I have to confest this here I can say if two color fits each other estetically (meaning I can taste good design :) ) but I do not have much ability about turning some sketch into actual design.</li>\n</ul>','2011-10-07 11:14:02','2011-10-07 11:29:25'),(21,1,'how-did-i-fail-from-my-microsoft-interview','HOW DID I FAIL FROM MY MICROSOFT INTERVIEW ?','<h2>Story Part</h2>\r\n<p><img src=\"/static/images/uploads/microsoft1.jpg\" align=\"left\" /></p>\r\n<p>Yes I try to join the dark side but i failed :). How come ? The actual journey started about 7 months ago while i was at the beginning of the 4th grade that I informed by Microsoft Recruiter with mail stating that they are interested in me for their full time positions at Redmond. Yes it was exciting news for me , that was one my dreams to work at Redmond from the moment I started my first grade at Computer Science. But there are some stages you have to pass or impress them or convince them that you are good enough to come to the one on one interview.  Let me tell you about how the hole interview process goes at Microsoft. First they got my resume which have to be good and professional enough so that they can contact with me for their open positions. Lets assume you have impressed them and passed this stage next thing you see in your inbox stating that \"hi we are from Microsoft and i am recruiter, we are impressed by your works and resume and we would like to conduct a phone interview with you\" kind of thing and you get excited more , then both decide a good interview day and time considering your local time, you can change interview day and time if the given ones does not fit with your calendar (but it must be reasonable excuse), i delay the interview about 2 times i think. And the interview day you are waiting front of the phone staring with empty eyes to phone, you are excited and phone rang with unknown number, &nbsp;oh bummer! you both experiencing problem with getting voice from the other side. Recruiter suggested to delay the interview to another day and after some more mailing between you and recruiter both decide to do this over Skype. You find a good internet connection and about 10 minutes before the interview time recruiter add you from Skype and interview begins. Recruiter tells you how the phone interview process works and said it last about 45 minutes. After introduction phase recruiter start asking some general questions, i will give some of the questions here that i have&nbsp; been asked</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Which position you are applying for ? (SDE/SDET)</li>\r\n<li>Why are you applying to this position ?</li>\r\n<li>How would you describe the good code ?</li>\r\n<li>What is the most compelling project you did and describe it and your job in project? (if its a team work more explanation)</li>\r\n<li>Why do you wanna work at Microsoft ? (you didnt expect this coming did you ? :) )</li>\r\n<li>What is ideal programmer look like grade yourself if ideal one is 10 ?</li>\r\n<li>Ok lets consider you have 1 month free at Microsoft after starting to work here, what do you wanna work on (technology, project) ?</li>\r\n<li>Assume we are shipping Xbox, you are the last person before shipping to test it , how would you test it ?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These are some of the general question i have been asked and i try to do my best to answer these questions and of &nbsp;course after these questions i have been asked technical questions, i am not gonna give that questions you can search and find similar tricky questions at all most all over the internet. But if i level the difficulties of the technical questions i can say they were between medium and hard.  And you looked at your time 45 minutes is over and recruiter say some procedural stuff stating that we will get back to you even if results are positive or negative within two weeks. You hang up the phone and you feel relief. After two weeks recruiter returns me with positive feedback and stated that \"we want to meet you and we will provide second interview location as soon as possible\". Again you send lots of email for visa,passport, location etc. As a result they decided on interviewing with me at Poland instead of Redmond. Because travelling from Turkey to Redmond-US would be exhausting for me they decide on Poland. I will now skip the other boring parts and continue with the how did i fail part.</p>\r\n<h2>You have to prepare well...</h2>\r\n<p>I could not prepare well for the interview cause I have projects on going, I&nbsp;was working at that time at <a href=\"http://www.turkcelltech.com/Default.aspx\">Turkcell Technology</a> on the other side I&nbsp;have classes at university and their midterm and projects, I participated in some mobile competitions get some good&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aveainovasyoncagrisi.com/blog/\">degree</a>s etc etc. This is one of the biggest reasons of my failure.</p>\r\n<h2>You have to know data structures, their complexity and trade-offs well...</h2>\r\n<p>I knew the data structures well, I was really practiced them at my projects especially the hard ones at university with C/C++. But after a while i move my primary language to Java, things started to change now my projects doesnt need a algorithmic thinking or some kind of data structure, \"oh we need a binary search, oh great java already have one lets use it no need to code it again\", if you do this about 2 year repeatedly you start to lose your&nbsp;competency about data structures and algorithms like which one is suitable for which situation, what is their complexity,what is their trade-off, which algorithm we should use and how to implement it. And then I realized the projects I involved or I created recently that can be easily done without any core CS education and they are not really showing my differences from a self thought programmer who doesnt have CS education. I am not saying the projects i have done were not good ones, they are good and innovative but most of them does not involve any context that i can use my CS knowledge. I think this is one of the main problem that students suffer in Turkey. I got a good education at university I have to show what makes me exceptional with my core CS knowledge, without using that knowledge I am just useless. This is second biggest reason of my failure.  I face with data structures and complexity question with my second interviewer. He is one of the <a href=\"http://www.microsoft.com/windowsphone/en-us/default.aspx\">Windows Phone 7</a> service developers at Redmond, he asked me to code some specific problems about link lists, searching algorithms and other data structures. I was again asked for some testing questions with given client-server architecture about how to testing and breaking it. I was not expecting but i was asked also some brain teaser questions, after some thinking time and with the suggestion of \"think outside of the box\" from him i can come up with answer.</p>\r\n<h2>You have to practice white board coding also know types of testing ( blackbox, whitebox )...</h2>\r\n<p>One of the things that I&nbsp;havent really practiced. <a href=\"http://blogs.msdn.com/b/ericlippert/archive/2004/04/15/114094.aspx\">This post</a> give a good grasp about white board coding written by one of Microsoft &nbsp;SDE ,<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black-box_testing\">Blackbox</a> testing, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitebox_testing\">whitebox</a> testing, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_testing\">regression</a> testing, positive test cases, negative test cases.</p>\r\n<h2>You have to good at code reading and finding bugs in given time</h2>\r\n<p>Other than asking questions they gave me some code that i should find if any bugs appear in it. Also you have to do some <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black-box_testing\">blackbox testing</a> on given function or module. Provide them some negative test cases or some positive test cases for the code. Until i got to interview i didnt realize that i couldnt developed myself at testing area of the software development but this was not totally my fault there are not classes at university talking about testing in a detailed way not just \"this is unit testing you test individual components of the code for use , this is integration testing you group the software parts of modules and test as a group, thats how testing done\" like giving detailed information about how blackbox testing done, how whitebox testing done and may be a project that students try to write a code that try to break the working one. I dont know these are just random thoughts come to my mind. You can say that testing does not have to be learned at university you can learn on your own or at work sadly i did not write too much test while i was working and didnt aim that software topic too but i wouldnt hurt someone to have this kind of classes at least as technical elective ( i am not even sure if any university in Turkey providing this kind of classes).  I talked about testing and how its done at Microsoft with my first interviewer he was a old Win 95 developer which started as a SDE then move to SDET position, he was one of the testters of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TrueType\">TTF (TrueTypeFonts)</a> at Windows but now he was one the tester of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_language_runtime\">.NET CLR (Common Language Runtime)</a> . I asked him lots of questions about transitions from SDE to SDET position cause even SDET\'s at Microsoft write much more code than SDE\'s purposes of the positions are different. I was not satisfied by his answers cause seems like this transition was not his choice but he answered my question very informative way including how testing done at Microsoft.</p>\r\n<h2>You have to read at least 5-6 of these books...</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Box, Don.&nbsp;<em>Essential .Net, Volume I: The Common Language Runtime</em>. Addison-Wesley Professional, 2003.</li>\r\n<li>Brooks, Fredrik.&nbsp;<em>The Mythical Man-Month: Essays on Software Engineering</em>. Addison-Wesley Professional, 1995.</li>\r\n<li>Cormen, T.h., Leiserson, C.E., Reivert, R.L., &amp; Stein, Cliff.&nbsp;<em>Introduction to Algorithms</em>. McGraw-Hill, 1990.</li>\r\n<li>Howard, Michael &amp; LeBlanc, David, eds.&nbsp;<em>Writing Secure Code</em>. Microsoft Press, 2001.</li>\r\n<li>Maguire, Steve.&nbsp;<em>Writing Solid Code: Microsoft\'s Techniques for Developing Bug-Free C Programs</em>. Microsoft Press, 1993.</li>\r\n<li>McConnell, Steve.&nbsp;<em>Code Complete: A Practical Handbook of Software Construction</em>. Microsoft Press, 1993.</li>\r\n<li>McConnell, Steve.&nbsp;<em>Rapid Development: Taming Wild Software Schedules</em>. Microsoft Press, 1996.</li>\r\n<li>Tanenbaum, Andrew.&nbsp;<em>Modern Operating Systems</em>. 2nd ed. Prentice Hall, 2011.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>You have to pass the interview bar...</h2>\r\n<p>Microsoft has a level bar at interviews if you pass that bar you will probably get an offer no matter what but if not ... you know the result :) . Overall of above reasons i couldnt pass the bar so i didnt got an offer.</p>\r\n<h2>Not all of the interview process pointless if result negative...</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>These headings with bold are also valid for interviews of other world wide tech companies like Amazon, Google, Facebook. From this post you can say that my interview went very bad and i couldnt answer even single question but its not like that. I answer almost all questions that they have asked to me but what prevent me from getting offer is that for every question they asked they raise the bar and want me to improve previous version of code (i am talking about complexity or general term more efficient way to do same job), if you havent practiced or not well prepared to this you will probably will fail too. I know result not good but there are some beneficial effects of this interview and the hole process. I got a really good interview experience really good one, see my weaknesses, achieve one of my dream (even getting to interview for full-time position at 4th grade is a satisfaction for me, not too much people got this chance ), had a chance to see Poland-Warsaw great city by the way. This does not mean that everything over, who knows maybe i will apply again... ;)</p>','<h2>Story Part</h2>\n\n<p><img src=\"/static/images/uploads/microsoft1.jpg\" align=\"left\" /></p>\n\n<p>Yes I try to join the dark side but i failed :). How come ? The actual journey started about 7 months ago while i was at the beginning of the 4th grade that I informed by Microsoft Recruiter with mail stating that they are interested in me for their full time positions at Redmond. Yes it was exciting news for me , that was one my dreams to work at Redmond from the moment I started my first grade at Computer Science. But there are some stages you have to pass or impress them or convince them that you are good enough to come to the one on one interview.  Let me tell you about how the hole interview process goes at Microsoft. First they got my resume which have to be good and professional enough so that they can contact with me for their open positions. Lets assume you have impressed them and passed this stage next thing you see in your inbox stating that \"hi we are from Microsoft and i am recruiter, we are impressed by your works and resume and we would like to conduct a phone interview with you\" kind of thing and you get excited more , then both decide a good interview day and time considering your local time, you can change interview day and time if the given ones does not fit with your calendar (but it must be reasonable excuse), i delay the interview about 2 times i think. And the interview day you are waiting front of the phone staring with empty eyes to phone, you are excited and phone rang with unknown number, &nbsp;oh bummer! you both experiencing problem with getting voice from the other side. Recruiter suggested to delay the interview to another day and after some more mailing between you and recruiter both decide to do this over Skype. You find a good internet connection and about 10 minutes before the interview time recruiter add you from Skype and interview begins. Recruiter tells you how the phone interview process works and said it last about 45 minutes. After introduction phase recruiter start asking some general questions, i will give some of the questions here that i have&nbsp; been asked</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Which position you are applying for ? (SDE/SDET)</li>\n<li>Why are you applying to this position ?</li>\n<li>How would you describe the good code ?</li>\n<li>What is the most compelling project you did and describe it and your job in project? (if its a team work more explanation)</li>\n<li>Why do you wanna work at Microsoft ? (you didnt expect this coming did you ? :) )</li>\n<li>What is ideal programmer look like grade yourself if ideal one is 10 ?</li>\n<li>Ok lets consider you have 1 month free at Microsoft after starting to work here, what do you wanna work on (technology, project) ?</li>\n<li>Assume we are shipping Xbox, you are the last person before shipping to test it , how would you test it ?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>These are some of the general question i have been asked and i try to do my best to answer these questions and of &nbsp;course after these questions i have been asked technical questions, i am not gonna give that questions you can search and find similar tricky questions at all most all over the internet. But if i level the difficulties of the technical questions i can say they were between medium and hard.  And you looked at your time 45 minutes is over and recruiter say some procedural stuff stating that we will get back to you even if results are positive or negative within two weeks. You hang up the phone and you feel relief. After two weeks recruiter returns me with positive feedback and stated that \"we want to meet you and we will provide second interview location as soon as possible\". Again you send lots of email for visa,passport, location etc. As a result they decided on interviewing with me at Poland instead of Redmond. Because travelling from Turkey to Redmond-US would be exhausting for me they decide on Poland. I will now skip the other boring parts and continue with the how did i fail part.</p>\n\n<h2>You have to prepare well...</h2>\n\n<p>I could not prepare well for the interview cause I have projects on going, I&nbsp;was working at that time at <a href=\"http://www.turkcelltech.com/Default.aspx\">Turkcell Technology</a> on the other side I&nbsp;have classes at university and their midterm and projects, I participated in some mobile competitions get some good&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aveainovasyoncagrisi.com/blog/\">degree</a>s etc etc. This is one of the biggest reasons of my failure.</p>\n\n<h2>You have to know data structures, their complexity and trade-offs well...</h2>\n\n<p>I knew the data structures well, I was really practiced them at my projects especially the hard ones at university with C/C++. But after a while i move my primary language to Java, things started to change now my projects doesnt need a algorithmic thinking or some kind of data structure, \"oh we need a binary search, oh great java already have one lets use it no need to code it again\", if you do this about 2 year repeatedly you start to lose your&nbsp;competency about data structures and algorithms like which one is suitable for which situation, what is their complexity,what is their trade-off, which algorithm we should use and how to implement it. And then I realized the projects I involved or I created recently that can be easily done without any core CS education and they are not really showing my differences from a self thought programmer who doesnt have CS education. I am not saying the projects i have done were not good ones, they are good and innovative but most of them does not involve any context that i can use my CS knowledge. I think this is one of the main problem that students suffer in Turkey. I got a good education at university I have to show what makes me exceptional with my core CS knowledge, without using that knowledge I am just useless. This is second biggest reason of my failure.  I face with data structures and complexity question with my second interviewer. He is one of the <a href=\"http://www.microsoft.com/windowsphone/en-us/default.aspx\">Windows Phone 7</a> service developers at Redmond, he asked me to code some specific problems about link lists, searching algorithms and other data structures. I was again asked for some testing questions with given client-server architecture about how to testing and breaking it. I was not expecting but i was asked also some brain teaser questions, after some thinking time and with the suggestion of \"think outside of the box\" from him i can come up with answer.</p>\n\n<h2>You have to practice white board coding also know types of testing ( blackbox, whitebox )...</h2>\n\n<p>One of the things that I&nbsp;havent really practiced. <a href=\"http://blogs.msdn.com/b/ericlippert/archive/2004/04/15/114094.aspx\">This post</a> give a good grasp about white board coding written by one of Microsoft &nbsp;SDE ,<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black-box_testing\">Blackbox</a> testing, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitebox_testing\">whitebox</a> testing, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_testing\">regression</a> testing, positive test cases, negative test cases.</p>\n\n<h2>You have to good at code reading and finding bugs in given time</h2>\n\n<p>Other than asking questions they gave me some code that i should find if any bugs appear in it. Also you have to do some <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black-box_testing\">blackbox testing</a> on given function or module. Provide them some negative test cases or some positive test cases for the code. Until i got to interview i didnt realize that i couldnt developed myself at testing area of the software development but this was not totally my fault there are not classes at university talking about testing in a detailed way not just \"this is unit testing you test individual components of the code for use , this is integration testing you group the software parts of modules and test as a group, thats how testing done\" like giving detailed information about how blackbox testing done, how whitebox testing done and may be a project that students try to write a code that try to break the working one. I dont know these are just random thoughts come to my mind. You can say that testing does not have to be learned at university you can learn on your own or at work sadly i did not write too much test while i was working and didnt aim that software topic too but i wouldnt hurt someone to have this kind of classes at least as technical elective ( i am not even sure if any university in Turkey providing this kind of classes).  I talked about testing and how its done at Microsoft with my first interviewer he was a old Win 95 developer which started as a SDE then move to SDET position, he was one of the testters of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TrueType\">TTF (TrueTypeFonts)</a> at Windows but now he was one the tester of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_language_runtime\">.NET CLR (Common Language Runtime)</a> . I asked him lots of questions about transitions from SDE to SDET position cause even SDET\'s at Microsoft write much more code than SDE\'s purposes of the positions are different. I was not satisfied by his answers cause seems like this transition was not his choice but he answered my question very informative way including how testing done at Microsoft.</p>\n\n<h2>You have to read at least 5-6 of these books...</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Box, Don.&nbsp;<em>Essential .Net, Volume I: The Common Language Runtime</em>. Addison-Wesley Professional, 2003.</li>\n<li>Brooks, Fredrik.&nbsp;<em>The Mythical Man-Month: Essays on Software Engineering</em>. Addison-Wesley Professional, 1995.</li>\n<li>Cormen, T.h., Leiserson, C.E., Reivert, R.L., &amp; Stein, Cliff.&nbsp;<em>Introduction to Algorithms</em>. McGraw-Hill, 1990.</li>\n<li>Howard, Michael &amp; LeBlanc, David, eds.&nbsp;<em>Writing Secure Code</em>. Microsoft Press, 2001.</li>\n<li>Maguire, Steve.&nbsp;<em>Writing Solid Code: Microsoft\'s Techniques for Developing Bug-Free C Programs</em>. Microsoft Press, 1993.</li>\n<li>McConnell, Steve.&nbsp;<em>Code Complete: A Practical Handbook of Software Construction</em>. Microsoft Press, 1993.</li>\n<li>McConnell, Steve.&nbsp;<em>Rapid Development: Taming Wild Software Schedules</em>. Microsoft Press, 1996.</li>\n<li>Tanenbaum, Andrew.&nbsp;<em>Modern Operating Systems</em>. 2nd ed. Prentice Hall, 2011.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>You have to pass the interview bar...</h2>\n\n<p>Microsoft has a level bar at interviews if you pass that bar you will probably get an offer no matter what but if not ... you know the result :) . Overall of above reasons i couldnt pass the bar so i didnt got an offer.</p>\n\n<h2>Not all of the interview process pointless if result negative...</h2>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>These headings with bold are also valid for interviews of other world wide tech companies like Amazon, Google, Facebook. From this post you can say that my interview went very bad and i couldnt answer even single question but its not like that. I answer almost all questions that they have asked to me but what prevent me from getting offer is that for every question they asked they raise the bar and want me to improve previous version of code (i am talking about complexity or general term more efficient way to do same job), if you havent practiced or not well prepared to this you will probably will fail too. I know result not good but there are some beneficial effects of this interview and the hole process. I got a really good interview experience really good one, see my weaknesses, achieve one of my dream (even getting to interview for full-time position at 4th grade is a satisfaction for me, not too much people got this chance ), had a chance to see Poland-Warsaw great city by the way. This does not mean that everything over, who knows maybe i will apply again... ;)</p>','2011-10-07 11:16:47','2011-10-07 11:21:25');
